{
  "query": "What are the typical outcomes when introducing seeds to restore peatland vegetation?",
  "relevant_summary": "Across studies, sown seeds of peatland herbs and shrubs/trees sometimes germinated, but germination success varied by species and site [1823, 1824]. Seedling survival was mixed: some heather seedlings survived for two years in a bog, whereas all germinated willow seedlings died within a month in a fen [1824]. Sowing shrub seeds sometimes increased cover of certain shrubs (e.g., manuka, naturally colonizing heather), though in some cases shrub cover was similar to unsown plots [1824]. Sowing herb seeds led to measurable cover of the sown herbs in several studies, but in at least one fen experiment herb cover was similar to unsown plots [1823]. Total vegetation cover sometimes increased in sown plots, though other studies reported no effect, and long-term effects could be absent [1823, 1824]. Effects on plant species richness/diversity were inconsistent: some studies reported increases, others decreases, and several found no change [1823, 1824]. In some cases, plots sown with herb seeds were colonized by wetland- or peatland-characteristic species [1823].",
