{
  "query": "As an alternative to prescribed burning for managing vegetation on fens, what are the effects of mowing or introducing grazing?",
  "relevant_summary": "Across fens and fen meadows, mowing/cutting: altered overall plant community composition in multiple replicated studies; increased cover of fen- or wet meadow-characteristic plants in several studies, though a single mow typically had no effect in some cases; increased total moss/bryophyte cover in most replicated studies, with single mows often showing no effect; reduced cover or abundance of several herb groups (including bindweed, reeds, sedges, purple moor grass and grass-like plants), though one study reported sedge cover increased when other interventions were also applied; effects on shrub cover were mixed, with single mows sometimes reducing shrubs and sometimes having no effect; effects on vegetation structure (height and biomass) were mixed; and overall plant species richness usually increased under mowing, while single mows often had no effect (1759). The season/timing of mowing influenced outcomes: one study found similar community change across spring, summer and autumn mowing, but another reported different plant community types after summer vs winter mowing; plant species richness increased more over two years in summer-mown plots than spring- or autumn-mown plots (1771). Introducing grazing: resulted in plant communities that differed from mown meadows; grazed fen meadows had fewer fen-characteristic species and fewer plant species overall than mown meadows; grazing increased cover of some herb groups (cottongrasses, sedges or all grass-like plants), reduced purple moor grass in one study but typically had no effect in another; cover of fen-characteristic mosses sometimes did not change, while Sphagnum cover was reduced in one study; shrub cover was reduced in one study but typically unaffected in another; and overall plant species richness increased after reinstating grazing in one study but typically showed no effect in another (1762). For invertebrates, fens managed by mowing had greater butterfly species richness than those managed by cattle grazing; recently cut fens had fewer large copper eggs than uncut fens, and large copper caterpillar survival was lower in recently cut fens and in fens cut in autumn or winter than in uncut fens (3950).",
